  "description": "¶What Lean is Lean 4 is a dependently typed functional programming language and interactive theorem prover. It serves two purposes at once: you can write executable programs in it, and you can state and prove mathematical theorems in it. These are the same activity — a proof is a program whose type is the proposition it proves.\nLean\u0026rsquo;s architecture has two layers:\nThe kernel: a small, trusted type checker that verifies proof terms. The kernel implements the Calculus of Inductive Constructions. If the kernel accepts a term, the proof is correct — there is no appeal to external authority. The elaborator: a front-end that translates human-readable Lean code into the kernel\u0026rsquo;s internal language. Tactics, implicit arguments, type inference, and metaprogramming all live in the elaborator. They make proofs easier to write without enlarging the trusted base. ¶Installation Lean 4 is installed through elan, a toolchain manager (analogous to rustup for Rust):\n",
